w.theguardian.com/music/2009/jul/12/mos-def-the-ecstatic-reviewed |title=CD: Pop Review: Mos Def, The Ecstatic |work=[[The Observer]] |accessdate=April 21, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6G3dQWcCE?url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2009/jul/12/mos-def-the-ecstatic-reviewed |archivedate=April 22, 2013 |url-status=live }}\n* {{cite magazine|ref=harv|last=Tyrangiel|first=Josh|authorlink=Josh Tyrangiel|date=May 18, 2009|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1898966_1898928_1898917,00.html|title=Mos Def's The Ecstatic \u2013 Summer Arts Preview|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=August 29, 2018}}\n* {{cite web|ref=harv |last=Vozick-Levinson |first=Simon |year=2009 |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2009/06/03/ecstatic |title=The Ecstatic |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=June 6, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6iJysryus?url=http://www.ew.com/article/2009/06/03/ecstatic |archivedate=June 17, 2016 |url-status=live }}\n* {{cite web|ref=harv|last=Wappler|first=Margaret|date=June 9, 2009|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2009/06/album-review-mos-defs-the-ecstatic.html|title=Album review: Mos Def's 'The Ecstatic'|work=[[Los Angeles Times|Pop & Hiss]]|accessdate=August 29, 2018}}\n* {{cite web|ref=harv |last=Young |first=Alex |year=2009 |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2009/08/album-review-mos-def-the-ecstatic/ |title=Mos Def \u2013 The Ecstatic |work=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=June 4, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6iJz5CIFV?url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2009/08/album-review-mos-def-the-ecstatic/ |archivedate=June 17, 2016 |url-status=live }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.okayplayer.com/news/mos-def-preservation-the-recstatic-track-by-track-mp3.html|title=Yasiin Bey x Preservation \u2014 The REcstatic Album Stream|author=Brie|work=[[Okayplayer]]|year=2013}}\n* {{cite web|author=MissFrolab|year=2009|url=http://frolab.com/2009/06/07/mos-def-the-ecstatic-liner-notes-in-photos-video/|title=Mos Def 'The Ecstatic' Liner Notes in Photos & Video|work=Frolab|access-date=June 6, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808133458/http://frolab.com/2009/06/07/mos-def-the-ecstatic-liner-notes-in-photos-video/|archive-date=August 8, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}\n* {{cite web|author=MissFrolab|year=2009|url=http://frolab.com/2009/06/16/mos-def-the-ecstatic-samples-originals/|title=Mos Def: The Ecstatic Samples & Originals|work=Frolab|access-date=June 5, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808084304/http://frolab.com/2009/06/16/mos-def-the-ecstatic-samples-originals/|archive-date=August 8, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://myspace.com/mosdef/music/album/the-ecstatic-18772158 ''The Ecstatic''] ([[Adobe Flash]]) at [[Myspace]] (streamed copy where licensed)\n* {{Discogs master|150399|type=album}}\n* [https://www.discogs.com/release/4656963 ''The REcstatic''] at Discogs\n* [https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/yasiin-bey-mos-def-the-recstatic-mixtape.87020.html?song-14123 ''The REcstatic''] (Adobe Flash) at ''HotNewHipHop'' (streamed copy where licensed)\n\n{{Mos Def}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Estatic, The}}\n[[Category:2009 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by J Dilla]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Madlib]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Oh No (musician)]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by The Neptunes]]\n[[Category:Downtown Records albums]]\n[[Category:Mos Def albums]]\n[[Category:Political hip hop albums]]\n[[Category:Political music albums by American artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{featured article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Ecstatic\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Mos Def]]\n| cover      = The Ecstatic.jpg\n| alt        = A red-tinted film still showing a boy jumping from one roof to another\n| released   = June 9, 2009\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Record Plant]] and Someothaship Connect in Los Angeles; [[Downtown Music Studios]] in New York City; Hovercraft Studios in Virginia Beach\n| genre      = [[Conscious hip hop]], [[alternative hip hop|alternative rap]]\n| length     = 45:34\n| label      = [[Downtown Records|Downtown]]\n| producer   = [[Georgia Anne Muldrow]], [[J Dilla]], [[Madlib]], Mos Def, [[Mr. Flash]], [[The Neptunes]], [[Oh No (rapper)|Oh No]], Preservation\n| prev_title = [[True Magic]]\n| prev_year  = 2006\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = The Ecstatic\n | type        = album\n | single1     = Life in Marvelous Times\n | single1date = November 4, 2008\n | single2     = Quiet Dog Bite Hard\n | single2date = January 13, 2009\n | single3     = Casa Bey\n | single3date = May 26, 2009\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''The Ecstatic''''' is the fourth [[album]] by American rapper [[Mos Def]]. It was released on June 9, 2009, by [[Downtown Records]]. After venturing further away from [[hip hop music|hip hop]] with an acting career and two poorly received albums, Mos Def signed a recording contract with Downtown and recorded ''The Ecstatic'' primarily at the [[Record Plant]] in Los Angeles. He worked with producers such as Preservation, [[Mr. Flash]], [[Oh No (rapper)|Oh No]], and [[Madlib]], the latter two of whom reused instrumentals they had produced on [[Stones Throw Records]]. Singer [[Georgia Anne Muldrow]], formerly of the record label, was one of the album's few guest vocalists, along with rappers [[Slick Rick]] and [[Talib Kweli]]. For its front cover, a still from [[Charles Burnett (director)|Charles Burnett]]'s 1978 film ''[[Killer of Sheep]]'' was reproduced in red tint.\n\nThe album has been described by music journalists as a [[conscious hip hop|conscious]] and [[alternative hip hop]] record with an eccentric, internationalist quality. Mos Def's raps about global politics, love, spirituality, and social conditions are informed by the [[zeitgeist]] of the late [[2000s (decade)|2000s]], Black [[internationalism (politics)|internationalism]], and [[Pan-Islamic]] ideas, incorporating a number of Islamic references throughout the album. Its loosely structured, lightly [[reverberation|reverbed]] songs use unconventional [[time signature]]s and [[sampling (music)|samples]] taken from a variety of international musical styles, including [[Afrobeat]], [[Soul music|soul]], [[Eurodance]], [[jazz]], [[reggae]], [[Latin music (genre)|Latin]], and [[Middle Eastern music]]. Mos Def titled ''The Ecstatic'' after one of his favorite novels, the 2002 [[Victor LaValle]] book, believing its titular phrase evoked his singular creative vision for the album.\n\n''The Ecstatic'' charted at number nine on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] in its first week of release and eventually sold 168,000 copies. Its sales benefited from its presence on Internet blogs and the release of a T-shirt illustrating the record's packaging alongside a label printed with a code redeemable for a free download of the album. A widespread critical success, ''The Ecstatic'' was viewed as a return to form for Mos Def and one of the year's best albums. He embarked on an international tour to support the record, performing concerts in North America, Japan, Australia, and the United Kingdom between September and April 2010. As his [[disc jockey|DJ]] on the tour, Preservation began to develop remixes of the album's songs, which he later released on the [[remix album]] ''The REcstatic'' in 2013.\n\n== Background ==\nIn 2006, Mos Def's third album ''[[True Magic]]'' was released haphazardly by [[Geffen Records]] to fulfill a contractual obligation while he was devoting more time to his acting career.<ref>{{harvnb|Samuel|2009}}; {{harvnb|Huff|2009}}.</ref> The quality of the album, along with his repeated ventures away from recording [[hip hop music|hip hop]], left \"some fans wondering if Mos Def's acting accomplishments were finally affecting his music\", ''[[PopMatters]]'' critic Quentin B. Huff later wrote.{{sfn|Huff|2009}} Speaking with [[Spank Rock]] for ''[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]'' magazine, Mos Def elucidated his artistic endeavors at the time: \"You have to experience life, make observations, ask questions. It's machine-like how things are run in hip-hop now, and my ambitions are different{{nbsp}}... To me the job of an artist is to provide a useful and intelligent vocabulary for the world to be able to articulate feelings they experience every day.\"{{sfn|Anon.|2009a}} After ending his tenure on Geffen, he signed a record deal with [[Downtown Records]] before recording ''The Ecstatic'' as his first album for the label.{{sfn|Samuel|2009}}\n\n== Recording and production ==\n[[File:Mosdef (300dpi).jpg|left|thumb|Mos Def in 2008|alt=A man holding a microphone, dressed in jeans, white dress shirt and tie, shown from the side]]\n''The Ecstatic'' was mostly recorded in sessions at the [[Record Plant]] in Los Angeles; the songs \"Twilight Speedball\", \"No Hay Nada Mas\", and \"Roses\" were partially recorded at Hovercraft Studios in Virginia Beach, Someothaship Connect in Los Angeles, and New York City's [[Downtown Music Studios]].{{sfn|Anon.(f)|n.d.}}\n\nMos Def worked with producers [[Mr. Flash]], [[Oh No (rapper)|Oh No]], [[Madlib]], and Preservation, who previously produced some of ''True Magic''{{'}}s songs. For ''The Ecstatic'', Oh No reused some of his productions from his 2007 album ''[[Dr. No's Oxperiment]]'', while Madlib incorporated samples from his ''[[Beat Konducta|Beat Konducta in India]]'' (2007) record. For \"Life in Marvelous Times\", Mr. Flash reused the beat from \"Champions\" \u2013 his 2006 collaboration with the French hip hop group [[TTC (band)|TTC]] \u2013 while \"History\" used a beat produced by [[J Dilla]] before his death.{{sfn|Patrin|2009}}\n\nWith Preservation, Mos Def produced \"Casa Bey\" after a 2006 trip to [[Rio de Janeiro]], where local rapper [[MV Bill]] introduced him to the music of [[Banda Black Rio]]. Mos Def and Preservation altered one of the band's songs \u2013 \"Casa Forte\", an instrumental featuring their characteristic blend of [[funk]], [[jazz]], [[soul music|soul]], and [[Music of Brazil|Brazilian rhythms]] \u2013 and used it as the beat.{{sfn|Richard|2009}} The original song title \u2013 meaning \"strong house\" in Portuguese \u2013 was changed to \"Casa Bey\"; Bey was Mos Def's family surname. According to him, he tried to enlist rappers [[Jay Electronica]], [[Black Thought]], and [[David Jude Jolicoeur|Trugoy]] for the song, but they all found it too difficult to rap over the instrumental.{{sfn|Anon.|2009a}}\n\nMos Def collaborated with singer [[Georgia Anne Muldrow]] and rappers [[Slick Rick]] and [[Talib Kweli]] \u2013 his partner in the rap duo [[Black Star (rap duo)|Black Star]].<ref>{{harvnb|Anon.(h)|n.d.}}; {{harvnb|Jones|2009}}.</ref> Muldrow sang and played piano on \"Roses\", which she originally wrote and recorded in 2008 for her album ''Umsindo'' (2009). She said Mos Def \"borrowed\" the song for ''The Ecstatic'' after they met through a mutual friend. \"They came over one day and started playing 'Roses.' He was singing the song and knew it. He said 'I wanna grab that.' I said, 'Man, I already got this as a single'. He just wanted that song. He snatched it up real quick\", she recalled in laughter.{{sfn|Anon.|2009b}}\n\nAlong with Madlib, Oh No, and J Dilla, Muldrow had been an affiliate of [[Stones Throw Records]]; according to journalist [[Nathan Rabin]], they collectively produced half of the album, lending its sound a \"sympathetic\" quality.{{sfn|Rabin|2009}} With ''The Ecstatic'', Mos Def said he wanted to offer listeners sincere, uninhibited observations about life and love, \"some truth and positive heart lift\", without the need for club songs. \"No disrespect to [the club]\".<ref>{{harvnb|Anon.|2009a}}; {{harvnb|Gundersen|2009}}.</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Music and lyrics ==\n{{Listen|pos = right\n |filename    = Auditorium - Mos Def.ogg\n |title       = \"Auditorium\"\n |description = On \"Auditorium\", Mos Def raps about daily struggles and global politics over a [[Middle Eastern music|Middle Eastern]]-influenced instrumental produced by [[Madlib]].{{sfn|Slavik|2009}}\n}}\n''The Ecstatic'' covers an international range of styles in a very loose and extemporaneous manner, held together by what Rabin described as \"a lyrical and sonic fascination with life beyond the Western World\".<ref>{{harvnb|Patrin|2009}}; {{harvnb|Rabin|2009}}.</ref> According to [[Robert Christgau]], the album's songs generally average two-and-a-half minutes and segue into one another without [[resolution (music)|resolution]], giving it the feel of a globally influenced hip hop [[mixtape]], \"with poles in [[Brooklyn]] and [[Beirut]]\".{{sfn|Christgau|2009}} The record reflects Mos Def's varied interests in [[jazz]], poetry, [[Eastern music|Eastern]] rhythms, [[psychedelia]], [[Spanish music]], and the [[blues]].{{sfn|Stewart|2009}} The tracks on the first half are, as ''[[The Observer]]''{{'}}s Ben Thompson described, \"predominantly eastward-looking\", while the second half indulges more in [[Latin music (genre)|Latin]] and [[reggae]] influences.{{sfn|Thompson|2009}} Other sounds sampled or explored include [[Afrobeat]] (\"Quiet Dog Bite Hard\"), [[Eurodance]] (\"Life in Marvelous Times\"), [[Bollywood]] (\"Supermagic\"), and [[Philadelphia soul]].<ref>{{harvnb|Kot|2009}}; {{harvnb|Patrin|2009}}; {{harvnb|Kellman|n.d.}}.</ref> \"Supermagic\" also draws on elements from Turkish [[acid rock]] and ''[[Mary Poppins (film)|Mary Poppins]]'', while on \"No Hay Nada Mas\", Mos Def sings and raps in Spanish over a [[flamenco]]-influenced production.<ref>{{harvnb|Kot|2009}}; {{harvnb|Patrin|2009}}; {{harvnb|Stewart|2009}}.</ref> He sings elsewhere on the album, often breaking into sing-song [[vamp (music)|vamps]] during his raps.<ref>{{harvnb|Kot|2009}}; {{harvnb|Patrin|2009}}.</ref> Along with Mos Def's singing, the predominantly sample-based music is unconventional in its use of what Preservation said are unusual [[time signature]]s and \"awkward\" [[breakdown (music)|breakdowns]].{{sfn|Balfour|2013}}\n\nAccording to ''[[The Independent]]''{{'}}s Simmy Richman, ''The Ecstatic''{{'}}s Eastern-influenced musical backdrop was reflective of Mos Def's \"post-[[War on Terror]]\" themes; Richman called it a [[conscious rap]] record, and ''No Ripcord''{{'}}s Ryan Faughnder regarded the music as \"socially conscious alternative hip-hop\".<ref>{{harvnb|Richman|2009}}; {{harvnb|Faughnder|2009}}.</ref> Mos Def incorporated a number of Islamic references onto the album, including samples of American Muslim activist [[Malcolm X]], Turkish protest singer [[Selda Ba\u011fcan]], and an Arab-language scene from the 1966 film ''[[The Battle of Algiers]]''; additionally, the track \"Wahid\" was titled after the Arabic word for \"oneness\". African-American studies and media scholar Sohail Daulatzai believed ''The Ecstatic'' is informed by Black [[Internationalism (politics)|internationalist politics]] and [[Pan-Islamic]] ideas, while ''[[State (magazine)|State]]'' magazine's Niall Byrne said it explores the theme of [[international relations]] on songs such as the [[Middle Eastern music|Middle Eastern]]-influenced \"The Embassy\" and \"Auditorium\", which features an [[Iraq]]-themed guest rap by Slick Rick.{{sfn|Daulatzai|2012|p=132}} On the former track, Mos Def raps from the perspective of an outsider about the lifestyle of an [[ambassador]] at a luxury hotel, while the opening song \"Supermagic\" critiques government treatment of [[minority groups]].<ref>{{harvnb|Christgau|2009}}; {{harvnb|Byrne|2009}}; {{harvnb|Anon.|2015}}.</ref>\n\n{{quote box|quoted = 1|quote=You're living at a time of extremism, a time of revolution, a time when there's got to be a change. People in power have misused it. And now there has to be a change and a better world has to be built and the only way it's going to be built is with extreme methods. And I, for one, will join in with anyone. I don't care what color you are, as long as you want to change this miserable condition that exists on this earth. Thank you.|source=\u2014 1964 [[Malcolm X]] speech sampled for the beginning of the album{{sfn|Anon.|2015}}|width=20%|align=left|style=padding:8px;|border=1px}}\n\nAs on Mos Def's other albums, he spoke a dedication to God in Arabic (\"Bismillah ar-Rahman ar-Raheem\") at the start of ''The Ecstatic'', before \"Supermagic\" began with a sample of Malcolm X's 1964 speech at [[Oxford Union]].<ref>{{harvnb|Daulatzai|2012|p=132}}; {{harvnb|St. John|2009}}; {{harvnb|Patrin|2009}}.</ref> The sample prefaces the album's \"small-globe statement\", ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' journalist Nate Patrin explained, indicating that Mos Def has \"a stake in something greater than just one corner of the rap world\".{{sfn|Patrin|2009}} Alex Young from ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' believed the speech introduces \"a political album encompassing global beats and viewpoints\".{{sfn|Young|2009}} According to ''[[Washington Post]]'' critic Allison Stewart, Mos Def seems equally interested in the [[Barack Obama|Obama]]-era zeitgeist as in accounts of the past, such as the early-1980s [[Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant, Brooklyn|Bedford\u2013Stuyvesant]] setting of \"Life in Marvelous Times\".{{sfn|Stewart|2009}} Young deemed the song anthemic for \"a seemingly paradoxical age that routinely sees events such as a Black man being elected president of a nation wallowing in racial inequality\".{{sfn|Young|2009}} From Christgau's perspective, Mos Def offers a [[credo]] in the lyrics: \"More of less than ever before / It's just too much more for your mind to absorb / It's scary like hell, but there's no doubt / We can't be alive in no time but now\".{{sfn|Christgau|2009}}\n\nThroughout ''The Ecstatic'', Mos Def alternates between what [[AllMusic]]'s Andy Kellman called nonsensical yet intellectual raps and \"seemingly nonchalant, off-the-cuff boasts\", set against eccentric, lightly [[reverberation|reverbed]] productions.{{sfn|Kellman|n.d.}} According to ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s Paul MacInnes, ''The Ecstatic'' features his characteristically \"fragmented lyrical style, which looped words within phrases and played on sound as much as meaning\".{{sfn|MacInnes|2009}} \"Auditorium\" showcases his \"complex and convoluted\" lyricism [[flow (music)|delivered]] closely in rhythm with the beat, Patrin said, citing the lines \"soul is the lion's roar, voice is the siren / I swing 'round, wring out and bring down the tyrant / chop a small axe and knock a giant lopsided\".{{sfn|Patrin|2009}} He explores [[Afrocentricism|Afrocentric]] themes on \"Revelations\" and compares love to a gunfight on \"Pistola\". On \"Roses\", Muldrow sings [[Environmentally friendly|nature-friendly]] lyrics about drawing flowers in times of sadness rather than plucking them from the ground. \"Roses is about creativity and human capacity\", she explained. \"A lot of times Western society makes [women] base our sense of worth on 'diamonds are forever' or 'a dozen roses' and that's how you prove your love to somebody{{nbsp}}\u2026 but you receive so many gifts and still feel empty. So draw them and let the roses come from inside.\"{{sfn|Anon.|2009b}}\n\n== Title and packaging ==\n[[File:Moorish Science Temple 1928 Convention.jpg|thumb|right|Attendees of the 1928 [[Moorish Science Temple]] Conclave; the photo was used for the album's back cover.|alt=A group of men and women facing forward, dressed in Arabic clothing, assembled outside a building]]\n\n''The Ecstatic'' was titled after [[Victor LaValle]]'s 2002 [[Black comedy|dark humor]] novel.{{sfn|Gundersen|2009}} One of Mos Def's favorite novels, it was written about an overweight college dropout who fell into mental illness while living with his eccentric family in [[Queens, New York]].<ref>{{harvnb|Samuel|2009}}; {{harvnb|Gundersen|2009}}.</ref> According to Mos Def, the phrase \"the ecstatic\" was \"used in the 17th and 18th centuries to describe people who were either mad or divinely inspired and consequently dismissed as kooks\".{{sfn|Gundersen|2009}} The phrase resonated with him, as he believed no one else in hip hop had ever recorded an album like ''The Ecstatic''. \"I feel like I was the only person who was capable of making this type of music in this type of way\", he claimed. \"I don't rap like nobody, I don't try to sound like nobody.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Gundersen|2009}}; {{harvnb|Anon.|2009a}}.</ref> He said \"the ecstatic\" also refers to \"a type of devotional energy, an impossible dream that becomes reality but is discredited before it's realized. The airplane, a nutty idea. The telephone, the Internet. People who envisioned those were considered radical or extreme.\"{{sfn|Gundersen|2009}}\n\n''The Ecstatic'' was packaged with few [[liner notes]] and a two-sheet booklet featuring a photo of Mos Def taken using the [[Photo Booth]] software application.{{sfn|Raible|2009}} The front cover photo reproduced a still in red tint from ''[[Killer of Sheep]]'', a low-budget 1978 film by [[Charles Burnett (director)|Charles Burnett]] about African-American life in 1970s [[Watts, Los Angeles]].<ref>{{harvnb|Patrin|2009}}; {{harvnb|Eisinger|2013}}.</ref> According to Dale Eisinger from ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'', the \"subtle and still-moving\" front cover photo reflects the ideas of cultural justice and global inequality present throughout Mos Def's career while capturing the \"sonic construction\" of ''The Ecstatic''{{'}}s music. \"The cover has hazy, dream-like movement\", Eisinger said, \"appearing as a non-narrative, loose collection of vignettes that are tangentially fascinating and incredibly powerful.\"{{sfn|Eisinger|2013}} For the back cover, a 1928 photo of the [[Moorish Science Temple]] gathering in Chicago was used, which Daulatzai interpreted as another element of Mos Def's \"Pan-Islamic mashup\" on the album.{{sfn|Daulatzai|2012|p=132}}\n{{clear}}\n\n== Marketing and sales ==\n\n''The Ecstatic'' was released by Downtown on June 9, 2009.{{sfn|Anon.(h)|n.d.}} In its first week, the album sold 39,000 copies and debuted at number nine on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], becoming the second record of Mos Def's career to reach the top 10 on the chart.<ref>{{harvnb|Anon.(h)|n.d.}}; {{harvnb|Caulfield|2009}}.</ref> The following week, he became the first recording artist to endorse the Original Music Tee, a T-shirt featuring the album cover on the front, the track listing on the back, and a tag with a code to download an [[MP3]] copy of the record.{{sfn|Michaels|2009}} The marketing strategy led to enough sales that ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' factored the T-shirts as album units on [[Billboard charts|the magazine's music charts]].{{sfn|Owsinski|2009|p=70}} ''The Ecstatic'' also benefited from the number of mentions it received on Internet [[blog]] posts, which peaked during the week of June 29.{{sfn|Siehndel|Abel|Diaz-Aviles|Henze|2013|p=279}} The album reached 168,000 copies sold in March 2014.{{sfn|Baker|2014}}\n\nThree [[single (music)|singles]] were released to promote the album: \"Life in Marvelous Times\" on November 4, 2008; \"Quiet Dog Bite Hard\" on January 13, 2009; and \"Casa Bey\" on May 26.<ref>{{harvnb|Samuel|2008}}; {{harvnb|Anon.(d)|n.d.}}; {{harvnb|Anon.(c)|n.d.}}.</ref> According to [[Charles Aaron]], \"Life in Marvelous Times\" was the \"most powerful and accessible song\" Mos Def had ever recorded, but it could not even manage to receive airplay on radio stations in his native New York. \"If [it] can't get on the radio, then I don't need to be on the radio\", the rapper said in August, expressing a wavering interest in reaching mainstream audiences.{{sfn|Aaron|2009|p=78}} \n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 7.7/10{{sfn|Anon.(e)|n.d.}}\n| MC = 81/100{{sfn|Anon.(h)|n.d.}}\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}{{sfn|Kellman|n.d.}}\n| rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev2Score = B+{{sfn|Vozick-Levinson|2009}}\n| rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|4|5}}{{sfn|MacInnes|2009}}\n| rev4 = ''[[The Irish Times]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|4|5}}{{sfn|Carroll|2009}}\n| rev5 = ''[[MSN Music]]'' ([[Robert Christgau#Consumer Guide|Consumer Guide]])\n| rev5Score = A{{sfn|Christgau|2009}}\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6Score = 8/10{{sfn|Patrin|2009}}\n| rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|3|5}}{{sfn|Hoard|2009}}\n| rev8 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev8Score = 9/10{{sfn|Aaron|2009|p=80}}\n| rev9 = ''[[The Times]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|5|5}}{{sfn|Potton|2009}}\n| rev10 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}{{sfn|Jones|2009}}\n}}\n''The Ecstatic'' was met with widespread critical acclaim.{{sfn|Anon.(h)|n.d.}} After two poorly received records by Mos Def, it was viewed by critics as a return to the form of his 1999 debut album ''[[Black on Both Sides]]'', earning some of the best reviews of his career.<ref>{{harvnb|Huff|2009}}; {{harvnb|Bronson|2009}}.</ref> At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, ''The Ecstatic'' received an [[weighted arithmetic mean|average]] score of 81, based on 28 reviews.{{sfn|Anon.(h)|n.d.}} Aggregator [[AnyDecentMusic?]] gave it 7.7 out of 10, based on their assessment of the critical consensus.{{sfn|Anon.(e)|n.d.}}\n\nIn ''[[The New Yorker]]'', ''The Ecstatic'' was hailed as Mos Def's \"most conceptually knotty and ambitious work\", while Aaron wrote in ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' that the \"internationalist return to form\" is also \"perhaps his liveliest work\".<ref>{{harvnb|Anon.|2016}}; {{harvnb|Aaron|2009|p=80}}</ref> For ''[[The Irish Times]]'', [[Jim Carroll (journalist)|Jim Carroll]] said the rapper has not performed this engagingly or skillfully since his career beginnings, highlighting especially \"Supermagic\" and \"Life in Marvelous Times\".{{sfn|Carroll|2009}} Mick Middles from ''[[The Quietus]]'' appraised it as \"the joyful sound of a rampant artist, unrestrained by expectation or commercialism\", with free-flowing music that escapes the boundaries his previous albums had merely pushed.{{sfn|Middles|2009}} Ben Thompson, in ''The Observer'', believed the diverse range of samples make it \"a crate-digger's wet dream\" and \"a thrillingly accessible demonstration of hip-hop's limitless creative possibilities\" to a layperson.{{sfn|Thompson|2009}} Writing for ''[[MSN Music]]'', Christgau felt the songs are \"devoid of [[hook (music)|hooks]] but full of sounds you want to hear again\", along with \"thoughtfully slurred\" yet intelligible lyrics by Mos Def, whose creative vision warrants the introductory Malcolm X sample.{{sfn|Christgau|2009}} In the opinion of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s [[Josh Tyrangiel]], his political meditations may not appeal to [[Conservatism in the United States|conservatives]] but are rich in \"the rhythm, exuberance and wit Mos Def showed on his early records\".{{sfn|Tyrangiel|2009}} Steve Jones of ''[[USA Today]]'' said his reflections on politics, love, religion, and societal conditions are full of insight and sincerity while calling the album his strongest effort.{{sfn|Jones|2009}}\n\nSome reviewers were less impressed. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' critic Christian Hoard found the quality of the songs inconsistent, while ''[[Slant Magazine]]''{{'}}s Eric Henderon claimed much of the music lacks [[song structure]] and \"careen[s] wildly, free from the constraints of chorus and verse\".<ref>{{harvnb|Henderson|2009}}; {{harvnb|Hoard|2009}}.</ref> Margaret Wappler evaluated the record with qualified praise in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', saying it \"mostly lives up to its giddy name\" but wanes occasionally while the artful samples may challenge listeners at first.{{sfn|Wappler|2009}}\n\nAt the end of 2009, ''The Ecstatic'' was named one of the year's 10 best albums; according to [[Acclaimed Music]], it was the 24th most prominently ranked record on critics' year-end lists.<ref>{{harvnb|Anon.|2010b}}; {{harvnb|Anon.(b)|n.d.}}.</ref> The album was ranked 30th by ''The Guardian'', 24th by ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'', 23rd by ''Slant Magazine'', 17th by ''Rolling Stone'', 16th by [[Sputnikmusic]], 15th by ''PopMatters'', 12th by ''[[Spex (magazine)|Spex]]'', 10th by ''[[Relevant (magazine)|Relevant]]'', 7th by ''Spin'', and 3rd by [[eMusic]]; [[About.com]] and [[BBC Music]] both named it the year's best rap record.<ref>{{harvnb|Anon.(b)|n.d.}}; {{harvnb|Anon.(a)|n.d.}}.</ref> In ''[[The Village Voice]]''{{'}}s [[Pazz & Jop]] \u2013 an annual poll of American critics nationwide \u2013 ''The Ecstatic'' was voted the 11th best album of 2009.{{sfn|Anon.(b)|n.d.}} Christgau, the poll's creator, ranked it 12th on his own year-end list for ''[[The Barnes & Noble Review]]''.{{sfn|Christgau|2010}} ''[[The Times]]'' placed it at number 30 on the newspaper's decade-end list of the 100 greatest records from the 2000s. It finished at numbers 27 and 155 on similar lists published by [[Napster (streaming music service)|Rhapsody]] and [[Rock's Backpages]], respectively.{{sfn|Anon.(b)|n.d.}} It was also nominated for a [[52nd Annual Grammy Awards|2010 Grammy Award]] in the category of [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Album|Best Rap Album]], while \"Casa Bey\" was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Solo Performance|Best Rap Solo Performance]].{{sfn|Harling|2009}} In 2013, ''[[Beats Per Minute (website)|Beats Per Minute]]'' named ''The Ecstatic'' the 112th best album of the past five years.{{sfn|Anon.(b)|n.d.}}\n\n== Touring ==\n[[File:Mos Def at the New Parish 2009.jpg|thumb|Mos Def performing at the New Parish in Oakland, October 2009]]\nMos Def supported the album with an international tour, which began its North American leg in early August 2009. This stretch of concerts saw the rapper play a number of US and Canadian cities, including Chicago, Miami, Washington D.C., Miami, Portland, Calgary, and Vancouver. Jay Electronica performed as his [[opening act]], and certain shows were [[Headliner (performances)|co-headlined]] with Kweli and singer [[Erykah Badu]].{{sfn|Dantana|2009}} The leg concluded on October 3 with an evening performance slot at the [[Austin City Limits Music Festival]].{{sfn|Keyes|2009}} Mos Def continued touring into the following year, playing a series of concerts in Japan during late 2009, which were documented in an episode of the [[Current TV]] series ''Embedded''. This was followed by his first headlining tour of Australia in January 2010 and a short series of April concerts in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{harvnb|Murray|2010}}; {{harvnb|Maness|2009}}; {{harvnb|Anon.|2010a}}.</ref>\n\n== Photo exhibition ==\nBetween January 30 and February 6, 2010, the HVW8 Art & Design Gallery in Los Angeles held an exclusive one-week exhibition titled \"Mos Def: Ecstatic Moments \u2013 Photographs\". It showcased a collection of photos taken by Cognito \u2013 a longtime hip hop documentarian and colleague of Mos Def \u2013 capturing the rapper during the two years spent making and promoting ''The Ecstatic''. Included in the exhibition were [[candid photograph]]s of him in the studio with the album's producers, and photos of his experiences visiting and touring locations around the world, including the [[Cape of Good Hope]] and [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]. A series of \"posse shots\" taken at the end of concerts from the American tour were also displayed, showing the rapper with Jay Electronica, Kweli, Badu, and musician [[Shuggie Otis]], who made an unexpected appearance during the tour.{{sfn|Anon.|2010b}}\n\nThe timing of the exhibition was meant to capitalize on Mos Def's two nominations for the Grammy Awards, which were being held that week, Cognito explained: \"I thought it was a perfect time to honor his presence while he's here. We've had a lot of our greats pass away in the past couple of years, be it Dilla or [[Slum Village|Bataan]] [''[[sic]]''], or whoever, and now everybody wants to talk 'Dilla Dilla Dilla' or whatever, but you weren't saying that while he was alive. Let's praise our heroes while they're alive.\"{{sfn|Ford|2010}}\n\n== Remix album ==\n[[File:Preservation in Budapest 2007 - 01.jpg|left|thumb|Preservation in 2007|alt=A man wearing eyeglasses, a beanie, scarf, and black sweatshirt, looking down at a set of turntables and other DJ equipment]]\n\nWhile on tour as Mos Def's in-concert [[disc jockey|DJ]], Preservation began to [[remix]] some of ''The Ecstatic''{{'}}s songs for their live routine. He challenged himself to remix the rest of the record, taking more than a year, as a project called ''The REcstatic'', working with Jan Fairchild, the original album's [[audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing engineer]].<ref>{{harvnb|Balfour|2013}}; {{harvnb|Lamb|2013}}.</ref> Preservation revisited sources for the original beats to find similar recordings that would correspond to each song's particular aesthetic while preserving Mos Def's vocals for the remixes.{{sfn|Lamb|2013}} He wanted them to be sample-based and consistent in [[key (music)|key]], [[pitch (music)|pitch]], and [[musical tone|tone]] to the first album, which he found difficult to achieve because of the original music's unorthodox instrumentals and singing. \"It's the result of countless hours of digging through records to sample\", he recalled. \"Constructing the beat, wrapping it around the vocal, adjusting the tempo, and so on\".{{sfn|Lamb|2013}} \"Black Fantastic\", an outtake produced by Minnesota during ''The Ecstatic''{{'}}s recording, replaced \"Casa Bey\" in the final track listing, as Preservation had found the tempo and structure of the original song too difficult to make a satisfactory remix.{{sfn|Balfour|2013}}\n\n''The REcstatic'' was released as a free download on June 12, 2013, by Preservation's [[imprint label]], Mon Dieu Music.{{sfn|Balfour|2013}} Reviewing the [[remix album]] in ''[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]'', Samuel Diamond said the rapturous energy of the original record was given a \"slightly rougher texture\" on what he deemed \"a respectful contribution to the canon of remix-based art, something that can be said for very few modern rap 'remixes'\".{{sfn|Diamond|2013}}\n{{clear}}\n\n== Track listing ==\nCredits are adapted from [[Downtown Music]].{{sfn|Anon.(f)|n.d.}}\n\n{{track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| title1 = Supermagic\n| writer1 = [[Mos Def|Dante Smith]], [[Oh No (musician)|Michael Jackson]]\n| extra1 = Oh No\n| length1 = 2:32\n| title2 = Twilite Speedball\n| writer2 = Smith, [[Chad Hugo]]\n| extra2 = [[The Neptunes]], Mos Def\n| length2 = 3:02\n| title3 = Auditorium\n| note3 = featuring [[Slick Rick]]\n| writer3 = Smith, [[Madlib|Otis Jackson Jr.]], [[Slick Rick|Richard Walters]]\n| extra3 = Madlib, Mos Def\n| length3 = 4:34\n| title4 = Wahid\n| writer4 = Smith, O. Jackson\n| extra4 = Madlib\n| length4 = 1:39\n| title5 = Priority\n| writer5 = Smith, Jean Daval\n| extra5 = Preservation\n| length5 = 1:22\n| title6 = Quiet Dog Bite Hard\n| writer6 = Smith, Daval\n| extra6 = Preservation\n| length6 = 2:57\n| title7 = Life in Marvelous Times\n| writer7 = Smith, [[Mr. Flash|Gilles Bousquet]]\n| extra7 = Mr. Flash\n| length7 = 3:41\n| title8 = The Embassy\n| writer8 = Smith, Bousquet, Ihsan al Munzer\n| extra8 = Mr. Flash, Mos Def\n| length8 = 2:45\n| title9 = No Hay Nada Mas\n| writer9 = Smith, Daval\n| extra9 = Preservation\n| length9 = 1:42\n| title10 = Pistola\n| writer10 = Smith, M. Jackson, Anthony Hester\n| extra10 = Oh No\n| length10 = 3:02\n| title11 = Pretty Dancer\n| writer11 = Smith, O. Jackson\n| extra11 = Madlib\n| length11 = 3:31\n| title12 = Workers Comp.\n| writer12 = Smith, Bousquet, [[Marvin Gaye]]\n| extra12 = Mr. Flash\n| length12 = 2:02\n| title13 = Revelations\n| writer13 = Smith, O. Jackson, Michael Drake\n| extra13 = Madlib\n| length13 = 2:03\n| title14 = Roses\n| no